1318→\mathbf{15} \;\oplus\; \overline{\mathbf{15}}
1319→  \;\oplus\; \mathbf{10} \;\oplus\; \overline{\mathbf{10}}
1320→  \;\oplus\; \mathbf{5} \;\oplus\; \bar{\mathbf{5}}\,,
1321→\end{equation}
1322→among which the $\mathbf{15} + \overline{\mathbf{15}}$ are
1323→the symmetric diquarks demanded by the sBootstrap counting
1324→(\S\ref{subsec:sym15}).
1325→
1326→Thus the sBootstrap representations
1327→$\mathbf{24} \oplus \mathbf{15} \oplus \overline{\mathbf{15}}$
1328→are exactly the $SU(5)$ content of the $SO(32)$ adjoint after
1329→restricting to the neutral sector.  However, $496 - 226 = 270$
1330→additional states with non-zero $U(1)$ charges must be projected
1331→out.  The mechanism for this projection---whether by an orbifold,
1332→a GSO-type condition, or a flux background---is an open problem.
1333→
1334→This embedding was first noted in \cite{Rivero2005}.  Its role
1335→here is to provide a UV origin for the symmetric $\mathbf{15}$
1336→that the Pauli theorem (\S\ref{subsec:pauli}) forbids at the
1337→level of point-particle composites: in the string picture,
1338→diquarks are open-string states whose symmetry is determined by
1339→the gauge group, not by Fermi statistics of constituents.
1340→
1341→%----------------------------------------------------------------------
1342→\subsection{Part B: The Casimir eigenvalue equation}
1343→\label{subsec:casimir_eq}
1344→%----------------------------------------------------------------------
1345→
1346→Consider the eigenvalue equation
1347→\begin{equation}
1348→\label{eq:casimir_quartic}
1349→x^2 \;+\; C_2\,x \;-\; C_2 = 0\,,
1350→\qquad C_2 = s(s+1)\,,
1351→\end{equation}
1352→where $C_2$ is the quadratic Casimir of $SU(2)$ at spin $s$ and
1353→$x = M^2/m^2$ for a mass scale $m$ to be determined.  This is a
1354→quadratic in $x$ (quartic in $M/m$).  Its solutions are
1355→\begin{equation}
1356→\label{eq:casimir_roots}
1357→x_{\pm}(s) = \frac{-C_2 \pm \sqrt{C_2^2 + 4C_2}}{2}\,.
1358→\end{equation}
1359→
1360→\paragraph{Structural constraints (codimension analysis).}
1361→The most general two-parameter family of such equations is
1362→\begin{equation}
1363→\label{eq:general_quartic}
1364→x^2 + (f_0 + f_1 C_2)\,x + (g_0 + g_1 C_2) = 0\,,
1365→\end{equation}
1366→with four real coefficients $(f_0, f_1, g_0, g_1)$.  Three
1367→structural conditions pin the polynomial to \eqref{eq:casimir_quartic}:
1368→\begin{enumerate}
1369→\item $f_0 = 0$: no spin-independent mass term;
1370→\item $g_0 = 0$: a massless eigenstate exists at $s = 0$;
1371→\item $g_1 = -f_1$: coefficient antisymmetry
1372→  (the constant and linear terms in $C_2$ are related).
1373→\end{enumerate}
1374→Together with the normalization $f_1 = 1$, these exhaust the
1375→freedom.  The ratio derived below is therefore a
1376→\emph{consequence} of these constraints, not a free parameter.
1377→
1378→\subsection{The electroweak ratio}
1379→\label{subsec:ew_ratio}
1380→
1381→Define the ratio
1382→\begin{equation}
1383→\label{eq:R_def}
1384→R \;\equiv\; 1 - \frac{x_+(1/2)}{x_+(1)}\,.
1385→\end{equation}
1386→Evaluating \eqref{eq:casimir_roots} at $s = 1/2$ ($C_2 = 3/4$)
1387→and $s = 1$ ($C_2 = 2$):
1388→\begin{align}
1389→x_+(1/2) &= \tfrac{1}{8}\bigl(-3 + \sqrt{21}\bigr)
1390→  \,,\quad\text{so } x_+(1/2)\,m^2 = M_W^2\,,
1391→\label{eq:xhalf}\\[4pt]
1392→x_+(1) &= -1 + \sqrt{3}
1393→  \,,\quad\text{so } x_+(1)\,m^2 = M_Z^2\,.
1394→\label{eq:xone}
1395→\end{align}
1396→The identification with $W$ and $Z$ is motivated by their
1397→spins ($s = 1/2$ maps to the $SU(2)_L$ doublet structure of $W$,
1398→$s = 1$ to the triplet).  Then
1399→\begin{equation}
1400→\label{eq:R_value}
1401→R = 1 - \frac{x_+(1/2)}{x_+(1)}
1402→  = \frac{(\sqrt{21} - 3)(\sqrt{21} - \sqrt{3}\,)}{16}
1403→  \;\approx\; 0.2231014\ldots
1404→\end{equation}
1405→
1406→This should be compared with the on-shell electroweak mixing
1407→parameter:
1408→\begin{equation}
1409→\label{eq:sin2_onshell}
1410→\sin^2\!\theta_W^{\text{os}}
1411→  \;\equiv\; 1 - \frac{M_W^2}{M_Z^2}
1412→  = 0.22306 \pm 0.00013\,,
1413→\end{equation}
1414→using $M_Z = 91.1876 \pm 0.0021\GeV$ and
1415→$M_W = 80.369 \pm 0.013\GeV$ (PDG~2024).
1416→
1417→Since $R = 1 - x_+(1/2)/x_+(1)$ and
1418→$\sin^2\!\theta_W = 1 - M_W^2/M_Z^2$, the two expressions are
1419→\emph{algebraically identical} once one identifies
1420→$x_+(s) = M^2(s)/m^2$.  The prediction $R \approx
1421→\sin^2\!\theta_W$ and the $W$-mass prediction derived below are
1422→therefore \textbf{one and the same observation}, not two
1423→independent tests.
1424→
1425→\paragraph{$W$-mass prediction.}
1426→From $M_W = M_Z\sqrt{1 - R}$:
1427→\begin{equation}
1428→\label{eq:MW_pred}
1429→M_W^{\text{pred}}
1430→  = 91.1876 \times \sqrt{1 - 0.22310}
1431→  = 80.374 \pm 0.002\GeV\,,
1432→\end{equation}
1433→which lies $0.39\sigma$ from the PDG average
1434→$M_W = 80.369 \pm 0.013\GeV$ and strongly disfavors the
1435→anomalous CDF-II measurement $M_W^{\text{CDF}} = 80.4335 \pm
1436→0.0094\GeV$ (6.2$\sigma$ tension with $R$).
1437→
1438→\paragraph{Scale parameter.}
1439→Setting $x_+(1)\,m^2 = M_Z^2$ gives
1440→\begin{equation}
1441→\label{eq:m_scale}
1442→m = \frac{M_Z}{\sqrt{\sqrt{3} - 1}}
1443→  = 106.577\GeV
1444→  \approx m_\mu \times 10^3\,,
1445→\end{equation}
1446→a coincidence whose significance is unclear.
1447→
1448→\subsection{Open issues for the Casimir equation}
1449→\label{subsec:casimir_open}
1450→
1451→\paragraph{Renormalization scheme dependence.}
1452→The comparison \eqref{eq:sin2_onshell} uses the on-shell
1453→definition $\sin^2\!\theta_W = 1 - M_W^2/M_Z^2 = 0.22306$,
1454→\textbf{not} the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ value
1455→$\sin^2\!\theta_W(\overline{\text{MS}}) = 0.23122 \pm 0.00004$.
1456→The two differ by $\Delta \approx 0.008$, far larger than
1457→experimental errors.  The algebraic argument
1458→\eqref{eq:casimir_quartic} contains no dynamical mechanism to
1459→prefer one scheme over the other.  Until such a mechanism is
1460→identified, the on-shell agreement should be regarded as
1461→suggestive but scheme-dependent.
1462→
1463→\paragraph{The fourth eigenvalue.}
1464→At $s = 1/2$, the second root of \eqref{eq:casimir_quartic} gives
1465→\begin{equation}
1466→\label{eq:fourth_root}
1467→|M(1/2, -)|
1468→  = m\,\sqrt{|x_-(1/2)|}
1469→  = 122.4\GeV\,,
1470→\end{equation}
1471→which is 2.3\% below $M_H = 125.25 \pm 0.17\GeV$.  However,
1472→this eigenstate carries spin $1/2$, while the Higgs boson is
1473→spin $0$.  The near-degeneracy is noted as a numerical curiosity;
1474→we do not claim a connection.
1475→
1476→\paragraph{Origin.}
1477→This observation was first made by H.~de~Vries in a Physics
1478→Forums discussion (November 2004) and subsequently studied in
1479→\cite{Rivero2005}.
1480→
1481→%----------------------------------------------------------------------
1482→\subsection{Independence of the two structures}
1483→\label{subsec:two_gap}
1484→%----------------------------------------------------------------------
1485→
1486→Parts~A and~B describe independent algebraic structures that share
1487→the same physical particles:
1488→\begin{itemize}
1489→\item The $SO(32)$ embedding (\S\ref{subsec:so32_chain}) governs
1490→  the \emph{representation content}---which $SU(5)$ multiplets
1491→  appear.
1492→\item The Casimir equation (\S\ref{subsec:casimir_eq}) governs
1493→  the \emph{mass/coupling pattern}---what numerical ratios emerge
1494→  among the gauge-boson masses.
1495→\item The two structures live over different number fields:
1496→  the adjoint decomposition involves only rational
1497→  dimensions, while the eigenvalue ratio $R$ lies in
1498→  $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{3},\sqrt{21}\,)$---an extension not
1499→  generated by any invariant of $SO(32)$.
1500→\end{itemize}
1501→No algebraic homomorphism linking the embedding chain
1502→\eqref{eq:so32_chain} to the eigenvalue equation
1503→\eqref{eq:casimir_quartic} has been found.  The gap between
1504→\emph{content} (which states exist) and \emph{dynamics}
1505→(what masses they acquire) remains the central open problem of
1506→the sBootstrap program.
